Here's how to set up switchable branded themes in .NET MAUI:

## 1. Define Theme Resource Dictionaries

Create a separate `ResourceDictionary` for each theme:

```xml
<!-- Resources/Styles/LightTheme.xaml -->
<ResourceDictionary xmlns="http://schemas.microsoft.com/dotnet/2021/maui"
                    xmlns:x="http://schemas.microsoft.com/winfx/2009/xaml"
                    x:Class="MyApp.Resources.Styles.LightTheme">
    <Color x:Key="PageBackground">#FFFFFF</Color>
    <Color x:Key="TextPrimary">#1A1A1A</Color>
    <Color x:Key="AccentColor">#0078D4</Color>
</ResourceDictionary>
```

```xml
<!-- Resources/Styles/DarkTheme.xaml -->
<ResourceDictionary ...  x:Class="MyApp.Resources.Styles.DarkTheme">
    <Color x:Key="PageBackground">#1E1E1E</Color>
    <Color x:Key="TextPrimary">#F0F0F0</Color>
    <Color x:Key="AccentColor">#4CC2FF</Color>
</ResourceDictionary>
```

```xml
<!-- Resources/Styles/HighContrastTheme.xaml -->
<ResourceDictionary ...  x:Class="MyApp.Resources.Styles.HighContrastTheme">
    <Color x:Key="PageBackground">#000000</Color>
    <Color x:Key="TextPrimary">#FFFFFF</Color>
    <Color x:Key="AccentColor">#FFFF00</Color>
</ResourceDictionary>
```

## 2. Create a Theme Service

```csharp
public enum AppTheme { Light, Dark, HighContrast }

public static class ThemeService
{
    public static void ApplyTheme(AppTheme theme)
    {
        var mergedDicts = Application.Current!.Resources.MergedDictionaries;

        // Remove the current theme dictionary (always the last one added)
        var existing = mergedDicts.FirstOrDefault(d =>
            d is LightTheme or DarkTheme or HighContrastTheme);
        if (existing != null)
            mergedDicts.Remove(existing);

        // Add the new theme
        ResourceDictionary newTheme = theme switch
        {
            AppTheme.Dark => new DarkTheme(),
            AppTheme.HighContrast => new HighContrastTheme(),
            _ => new LightTheme()
        };
        mergedDicts.Add(newTheme);

        // Persist the choice
        Preferences.Set("app_theme", theme.ToString());
    }

    public static void LoadSavedTheme()
    {
        var saved = Preferences.Get("app_theme", nameof(AppTheme.Light));
        if (Enum.TryParse<AppTheme>(saved, out var theme))
            ApplyTheme(theme);
    }
}
```

## 3. Bootstrap in App.xaml.cs

```csharp
public partial class App : Application
{
    public App()
    {
        InitializeComponent();
        ThemeService.LoadSavedTheme();
    }
}
```

## 4. Reference Theme Colors with `DynamicResource`

This is critical — use `DynamicResource` (not `StaticResource`) so values update at runtime:

```xml
<ContentPage BackgroundColor="{DynamicResource PageBackground}">
    <Label TextColor="{DynamicResource TextPrimary}" Text="Hello!" />
    <Button BackgroundColor="{DynamicResource AccentColor}" Text="Click" />
</ContentPage>
```

## 5. Settings Page Picker

```xml
<Picker x:Name="ThemePicker" Title="Theme"
        SelectedIndexChanged="OnThemeChanged">
    <Picker.ItemsSource>
        <x:Array Type="{x:Type x:String}">
            <x:String>Light</x:String>
            <x:String>Dark</x:String>
            <x:String>HighContrast</x:String>
        </x:Array>
    </Picker.ItemsSource>
</Picker>
```

```csharp
void OnThemeChanged(object sender, EventArgs e)
{
    if (ThemePicker.SelectedIndex < 0) return;
    var theme = (AppTheme)ThemePicker.SelectedIndex;
    ThemeService.ApplyTheme(theme);
}
```

---

**Key points:**

- `DynamicResource` is what enables live switching — it re-evaluates when the dictionary changes.
- Keep the same keys across all three dictionaries so bindings resolve regardless of active theme.
- `Preferences` persists the choice across app restarts.
- You can extend this with `Style` definitions inside each theme dictionary for more complex controls.
